ded targets rather than re-attacking a now-hardened platform\n\nHowever, some risk remains:\n- Unknown vulnerabilities may exist\n- Other threat actors may attempt to exploit Instructure's notoriety\n- Rushed patching could introduce new vulnerabilities\n\n**Adjustment from base rate: -5 to -7 percentage points**\n\n**Revised estimate: 10-12%**\n\n#### (i) Community Prediction Comparison\n\nNo community prediction provided in the prompt. If one exists and differs significantly from 10-12%, I would consider:\n- Whether the community is overweighting the \"repeat attacker\" risk (ShinyHunters may be satisfied)\n- Whether the community is underweighting the immediate hardening effect\n- Whether the community has information about additional vulnerabilities I'm not aware of\n\n---\n\n#### Final Reasoning\n\n**Why not higher (>25%)?**\n- Status quo bias: Most organizations don't experience repeat major breaches within 3 months\n- Immediate patching of known vulnerability eliminates the most obvious attack vector\n- Threat actor incentives: ShinyHunters has been paid; re-attacking risks their reputation\n- Heightened detection: Any new incident will be caught immediately\n\n**Why not lower (<5%)?**\n- Instructure's massive attack surface (275M users, 8,809 institutions) creates many targets\n- Known persistent threat actor with demonstrated capability\n- Likely security debt from previous breaches\n- 96-day window is not negligible\n- Ransom payment may incentivize other threat actors\n\n**Final estimate: 11%**\n\nThis reflects:\n- Elevated risk vs. typical organizations (base rate ~8-10%)\n- Significant risk reduction from immediate post-breach hardening\n- Acknowledgment that repeat major breaches within 3 months are uncommon\n- Realistic assessment of threat actor behavior and incentives\n\nProbability: **11%**\n\n",
